******
[2] Assam
Date: Fri 14 Aug 2015
Source: The Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Vector-sting-cripples-state/articleshow/48473091.cms


[With the exception of] Dima Hasao district, the entire state [of Assam] has been in the grip of vectorborne diseases this year [2015].

At least 291 people have succumbed to such diseases as of July 2015, health minister Nazrul Islam said in a written reply in the house on Thursday [13 Aug 2015].

[To date in 2015,] 95 people have died of Japanese encephalitis (JE), and 193 of acute encephalitis syndrome (AES). The state has reported 468 cases of JE and 571 cases of AES in 2015.

[As of] July, 15 people have died of JE and 22 of AES in Jorhat district. In Sivasagar district, 12 people have died of JE. Three malaria deaths have been reported from Bongaigaon, Kamrup (Rural) and Karbi Anglong districts.

Dhemaji, Golaghat and Sivasagar have reported the highest number of JE cases (41 each), followed by Dibrugarh (38), Tinsukia (37) and Jorhat (28). Sivasagar has reported the highest number of AES cases (50), followed by Dhemaji and Dibrugarh (43 each) and Golaghat (41).

Besides vaccination drives among adults and children, a task force has also been set up to contain the outbreak of vectorborne diseases in the state.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
